+---
+date: "2026-06-11"
+status: done
+implements: [FR-E83]
+tags: [cli, housekeeping, runs, journal]
+related_tasks: []
+---
+# `runs prune` — safe cleanup of old run directories
+
+## Goal
+
+Add a `flowai-workflow runs prune --workflow <dir> --keep <N> [--dry-run]`
+subcommand that deletes the oldest run directories under
+`<workflow-dir>/runs/` while never touching runs whose state is not
+provably terminal, never touching the run referenced by `runs/.lock`,
+and reporting a per-run summary (deleted / kept / skipped + reason).
+
+## Overview
+
+### Context
+
+- A run's only durable record is `runs/<run-id>/journal.jsonl`
+  (append-only recovery journal, FR-E69). Run status and start time are
+  reconstructed exclusively by replaying it with the existing replayer
+  `src/state/run-journal.ts::loadStateFromJournal` /
+  `replayRunJournal`. There is no other state source — `state.json` was
+  removed; a run directory without a replayable journal has unknown
+  state by definition.
+- Run-folder knowledge already has helpers that MUST be reused
+  (no duplicated path construction or replay logic):
+  - `src/state/state.ts::getRunDir(runId, workflowDir)` —
+    `<workflowDir>/runs/<run-id>`.
+  - `src/state/run-journal.ts::loadStateFromJournal(runDir)` — replay;
+    throws `Deno.errors.NotFound` when `journal.jsonl` is missing and
+    `Error` on malformed/empty journals.
+  - `src/state/lock.ts::defaultLockPath(workflowDir)` —
+    `<workflowDir>/runs/.lock`; `readLockInfo(lockPath)` — JSON
+    `{pid, hostname, run_id, started_at}`.
+- Terminal run statuses are `completed | failed | aborted`
+  (`RunState["status"]`; `run-journal.ts` has a private
+  `isTerminalStatus` helper to be exported and reused).
+- CLI parsing style (`src/cli.ts`): hand-rolled `for` loop over
+  `args`, `--flag value` and `--flag=value` forms, `throw new Error`
+  with a usage hint on bad input, exported pure `parse*Args` functions
+  unit-tested in `src/cli_test.ts`. Subcommand handlers catch, print
+  `Error: <msg>`, and exit non-zero.
+
+### Current State
+
+- Subcommands: `run`, `init`, `answer`, `mcp`. No `runs` command group;
+  no cleanup mechanism at all — `runs/` grows unboundedly.
+- `--help` (`printUsage`) lists every subcommand with usage lines.
+
+### Constraints
+
+- Follow the existing argument-parsing style in `src/cli.ts`; no new
+  dependencies.
+- Reuse `src/state/` helpers for run dir, journal replay, lock path and
+  lock format; do not duplicate logic that already has a helper.
+- Safety rules (hard requirements, from the request):
+  - NEVER delete a run whose replayed status is not terminal
+    (anything still running/pending/waiting is untouchable),
+    regardless of `--keep`.
+  - NEVER delete the run referenced by an existing `runs/.lock` file
+    (existence of the reference is enough — PID liveness is NOT
+    consulted; a stale lock still protects its run).
+  - Missing or unreplayable `journal.jsonl` counts as NOT terminal
+    (when in doubt, keep) and is reported as skipped with that reason.
+  - `--keep` must be a non-negative integer; anything else → clear
+    error + non-zero exit.
+- `--dry-run`: print what WOULD be deleted, delete nothing, exit 0.
+- No listing/inspection output beyond the prune summary; no remote
+  cleanup; no interactive prompts (out of scope per the request).
+- `deno task check` stays green. Tests must not test the `--help`
+  template text itself (project Test Rules: no constant/template
+  tests) — help presence is verified by an evidence command.
+- **Decision — `--keep` counting semantics:** `--keep N` retains the
+  `N` newest *deletable* runs (terminal + unlocked + replayable).
+  Protected runs (non-terminal, locked, unreplayable) are skipped and
+  do NOT consume the keep budget. Rationale: the safety rules already
+  allow the remaining total to exceed `N`; counting protected runs
+  toward `N` would make an unrelated protected run silently force
+  deletion of a newer terminal run — a protection should never widen
+  the deletion set ("when in doubt, keep").
+- **Decision — corrupt `runs/.lock`:** an unparseable lock file
+  references no run id, so it protects nothing by itself; every run
+  is still independently protected by the journal-status rules.
+- **Decision — ordering:** runs sort by replayed
+  `RunState.started_at` (ISO-8601 → lexicographic = chronological);
+  ties break by run-id descending for determinism. A replayable
+  journal whose `started_at` is somehow absent sorts as OLDEST
+  (deleted first among deletables) — status is still proven terminal,
+  so deletion stays safe; the rule only fixes ordering.
+
